<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="user-interviews">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>ux-researcher</domain>
    <summary>Conduct one-on-one conversations with users to understand their needs, behaviors, motivations, and pain points before designing solutions.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>ux-research</tag>
      <tag>interviews</tag>
      <tag>qualitative</tag>
      <tag>user-research</tag>
      <tag>methodology</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>beginner</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>User Interviews</title>

    <summary>User interviews are one-on-one conversations with users or potential users to understand their needs, behaviors, motivations, and pain points. Without understanding real user needs, design decisions are based on opinions rather than insights, resulting in features users do not want and frustration with the gap between design and reality.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Designing without understanding users means assumptions replace understanding, leading to solving wrong problems, poor user satisfaction, and wasted development effort. User interviews are the foundational method for discovering what users actually need rather than what we assume they need.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>In the discovery phase when the problem space is unclear and you need to understand user behaviors and motivations before designing anything.</item>
        <item>When you have a hypothesis about a user need and want to validate whether the underlying problem is real.</item>
        <item>After launch when unexpected usage patterns emerge in analytics and you need to understand why.</item>
        <item>When evaluating a design concept before committing to prototyping or development.</item>
        <item>When you need direct quotes and stories to persuade stakeholders who discount internal assumptions.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>When you need quantitative answers (how many? how often?) — use surveys or analytics instead.</item>
        <item>When users cannot articulate the relevant behavior (e.g., subconscious decision-making, habitual actions) — use observation or diary studies instead.</item>
        <item>When the research question is "do users prefer A or B?" — use preference testing or A/B testing instead.</item>
        <item>When no one on the team has time to analyze the data; interviews generate qualitative data that requires synthesis time — collecting without analyzing is waste.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="interview-types">
      <rule>
        <statement>Select interview type based on project phase and research goal.</statement>
        <rationale>Different interview types serve different research goals; mismatching type and goal produces data that does not answer the research question.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Exploratory (45-60 min): Understand problem space and user context.</item>
        <item>Generative (30-45 min): Generate ideas and expand the solution space.</item>
        <item>Evaluative (30-45 min): Test concepts, prototypes, or design ideas with users.</item>
        <item>Contextual (60-90 min): Observe users in their real environment while asking about their activities.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="step-1-define-objectives">
      <rule>
        <statement>Define research objectives before recruiting. Ask: What do you want to learn? What user decisions or behaviors are unclear?</statement>
        <rationale>Vague objectives lead to unfocused interviews and data that does not support decisions. Clear objectives guide question design and participant recruitment.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Behaviors: How do they currently do X?</item>
        <item>Motivations: Why do they do X?</item>
        <item>Pain points: What frustrates them about X?</item>
        <item>Needs: What would help them with X?</item>
        <item>Context: When/where do they do X?</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="step-2-recruit-participants">
      <rule>
        <statement>Recruit 5-8 participants per user segment. Include both current users and prospects. Ensure the participant pool matches your target user profile on relevant dimensions (role, experience level, usage patterns).</statement>
        <rationale>5-8 participants per segment is sufficient to reveal dominant themes and patterns. Smaller samples miss important themes; larger samples add time without proportional insight value. Homogeneous recruitment (all power users, for example) produces blind spots about how other user groups behave.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Customer database: Users who currently use your product.</item>
        <item>User panels: Recruited research participants willing to participate in studies.</item>
        <item>Social media: Targeted recruitment from online communities relevant to your problem.</item>
        <item>Professional recruiters: Agencies that specialize in finding specific user profiles (paid option).</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="step-3-prepare-interview-guide">
      <rule>
        <statement>Structure interviews: Introduction (5 min) → Warm-up (5 min) → Main questions (25-40 min) → Wrap-up (5 min). Use open-ended questions. Avoid leading questions and hypotheticals.</statement>
        <rationale>Structure ensures consistency across interviews and time-efficient data collection. Open-ended questions elicit the participant's perspective rather than confirming the interviewer's assumptions. Leading questions ("Don't you think the app is too complicated?") bias answers toward what the interviewer wants to hear.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Ask about specific past behavior and concrete examples, not hypotheticals or general opinions.</statement>
        <rationale>Recall of recent specific events is accurate; hypothetical responses overestimate intent ("Would you use a feature...?" reliably overestimates adoption). Ask "Tell me about the last time you..." not "How do you typically...?"</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Open-ended questions: "Tell me about...", "Walk me through...", "What was the most frustrating part?"</item>
        <item>Probing questions: "Why is that?", "Can you give me an example?", "How did that make you feel?"</item>
        <item>Avoid leading questions: Good: "How would you describe your experience?" Bad: "Don't you think this is too complicated?"</item>
        <item>Avoid closed yes/no questions: Good: "Tell me about your experience with feature X." Bad: "Do you like feature X?"</item>
        <item>Avoid hypotheticals: Good: "When have you needed to do something like Y?" Bad: "Would you use a feature that does Y?"</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="step-4-conduct-interviews">
      <rule>
        <statement>Build rapport. Listen more than talk. Follow interesting threads. Take notes or record with consent. Stay neutral in your reactions.</statement>
        <rationale>Rapport makes participants comfortable sharing candid feedback. Listening allows you to hear the participant's perspective rather than confirming your assumptions. Neutrality prevents social desirability bias (participants saying what they think you want to hear).</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Small talk at start builds comfort; comfortable participants share more openly.</item>
        <item>Active listening signals genuine interest; participants elaborate more when they feel heard.</item>
        <item>Silence after a participant finishes an answer is a tool; wait 3-5 seconds and participants often add the most revealing information.</item>
        <item>Do not react positively or negatively; do not share your opinions; do not defend the product.</item>
        <item>Record every session with explicit consent; memory and notes alone are unreliable for verbatim quotes needed for stakeholder communication.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="step-5-analyze-and-synthesize">
      <rule>
        <statement>Debrief immediately after each session while memory is fresh. Transcribe or summarize notes within 24 hours; memory degrades significantly after that.</statement>
        <rationale>Fresh memory captures nuance and emotional tone that fade within hours. Delayed analysis forces re-interpretation from incomplete notes.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Distinguish between "what participants said" (observation) and "what it means" (interpretation) in your notes. Conflating them bakes assumptions into findings.</statement>
        <rationale>Observation: "Three participants mentioned difficulty finding the export button." Interpretation: "Users struggle with discoverability." The interpretation may be wrong; the observation is a fact to be interpreted.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Identify recurring themes (present in 3+ interviews) separately from outlier insights (1-2 interviews but significant). Require exact participant counts when synthesizing; avoid "consensus illusions" where a theme from 2 of 6 interviews is presented as universal.</statement>
        <rationale>Themes recurring across multiple participants are more reliable signals. Outliers are still valuable (edge cases reveal product constraints) but must not be conflated with dominant patterns. Exact counts prevent over-generalizing.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Affinity mapping: Write each insight on a sticky note, group by theme, identify patterns.</item>
        <item>Insight statement format: "[User type] needs [need] because [motivation]. Currently, [pain point/gap]."</item>
        <item>Document null results; undocumented null results cause teams to run the same tests repeatedly.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="recommended-subagents">
      <list>
        <item>faion-sdd-executor-agent — generate interview guide from research objectives, synthesize interview notes into themed insights, draft a research findings report.</item>
        <item>General Claude subagent — review draft questions for leading language, suggest probing follow-ups, generate insight statements from raw notes.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="prompt-pattern">
      <p>You are a UX researcher preparing an interview guide for the following research objective: "[Research objective]" Target participant: [Description of participant profile]. Generate: 1. 3-5 warm-up questions (low stakes, build rapport); 2. 8-12 main questions covering: [topics]; 3. For each main question, suggest 1-2 probing follow-ups. Rules: No leading questions. No hypotheticals ("would you..."). Ask about specific past behavior, not general opinions.</p>
      <p>Here are notes from [N] user interviews on the topic of [topic]: [Paste notes]. Identify: 1. Recurring themes (present in 3+ interviews); 2. Outlier themes (1-2 interviews but significant); 3. Direct quotes that best illustrate each theme; 4. Contradictions between participants. Format as an affinity map structure ready for team review.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>An agent is most useful in the preparation and synthesis phases, not the interview itself. Pre-interview: an agent can generate a draft interview guide from a research objective, review it for leading questions, and suggest probing follow-ups. Post-interview: an agent can transcribe recordings (with a transcription service), identify recurring themes across notes from multiple sessions, draft an affinity diagram structure, and produce an insight report draft.</p>
      <p>The interview itself must be conducted by a human — rapport, real-time follow-up, and non-verbal cues cannot be replicated by an agent. A human must also validate synthesized themes before they are used to inform design decisions.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Record every session with explicit consent; memory and notes are unreliable for verbatim quotes, which are high-value for stakeholder communication.</item>
        <item>Start with the most recent specific event ("Tell me about the last time you...") before asking about general patterns — specific events are more reliable than reconstructed summaries.</item>
        <item>Silence is a tool; after a participant finishes an answer, wait 3-5 seconds before speaking — participants often add the most revealing information when they fill the silence.</item>
        <item>Debrief immediately after each session while memory is fresh; notes degrade significantly within 24 hours.</item>
        <item>Recruit participants who have done the relevant behavior recently (within 2-4 weeks) for episodic recall tasks; older experiences produce more reconstructed and less reliable data.</item>
        <item>When synthesizing, distinguish between "what participants said" (observation) and "what it means" (interpretation) in your notes — conflating them bakes assumptions into research findings.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools">
      <list>
        <item>whisper (OpenAI): Local audio transcription of recorded interviews. Install: pip install openai-whisper. Docs: github.com/openai/whisper</item>
        <item>ffmpeg: Convert audio/video interview recordings to supported formats. Install: brew install ffmpeg. Docs: ffmpeg.org</item>
        <item>otter.ai CLI: Transcription service integration. Third-party wrappers available.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="services-and-apps">
      <list>
        <item>User Interviews (SaaS): Participant recruitment panel; scheduling and screener management. Partial API support.</item>
        <item>Calendly (SaaS): Interview scheduling automation; webhook-driven. Yes (REST API).</item>
        <item>Otter.ai (SaaS): Auto-transcription; export as text for agent processing. Partial (export).</item>
        <item>Dovetail (SaaS): Research repository; tag-based analysis; API for data access. Partial (API).</item>
        <item>Grain (SaaS): Video recording + AI highlights; no programmatic API. No.</item>
        <item>Lookback (SaaS): Live and recorded user research sessions. No.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Do not ask an agent to identify insights from raw notes without first validating the transcription accuracy — transcription errors propagate into analysis.</item>
        <item>Agent-generated interview guides often include double-barreled questions ("How do you find the product and what do you like about it?") — always human-review the generated guide.</item>
        <item>Agents default to generating leading questions when given a product brief with an implicit positive framing; prompt explicitly to check for leading language.</item>
        <item>LLM synthesis can create "consensus illusions" — presenting a theme as universal when it appeared in 2 of 6 interviews; require the agent to state exact participant counts.</item>
        <item>Agent affinity diagrams are useful starting points but collapse nuance; human review of the raw quotes is required before the themes are finalized.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="limitations-and-biases">
      <rule>
        <statement>Be aware of and document the limitations of user interview findings.</statement>
        <rationale>Understanding where method breaks down prevents over-applying the findings beyond their scope.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Social desirability bias: participants say what they think the interviewer wants to hear, especially about sensitive behaviors.</item>
        <item>Recall bias: asking about past behavior produces reconstructed memory, not accurate accounts. Recent specific events are more reliable than general patterns.</item>
        <item>Hypothetical questions produce unreliable data; "would you use a feature that..." reliably overestimates intent.</item>
        <item>5-8 participants per segment reveals dominant themes but misses rare-but-important edge cases.</item>
        <item>Interview findings cannot be generalized statistically to the broader population; they reveal themes and possibilities, not frequencies.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/interview-guide.md" purpose="Interview guide with introduction script, warm-up questions, main questions by topic, and wrap-up."/>
      <template path="templates/interview-notes.md" purpose="Interview notes template capturing participant profile, key quotes, observations, pain points, needs, behaviors, and surprising insights."/>
    </templates>

    <checklist>
      <check>Research objectives defined and documented.</check>
      <check>Interview guide prepared with open-ended questions (no leading questions).</check>
      <check>Participants recruited matching target user profile (5-8 per segment minimum).</check>
      <check>Recording equipment tested; consent obtained before recording.</check>
      <check>Notes taken during interview or recording captured.</check>
      <check>Debrief completed immediately after session.</check>
      <check>Transcription or summary completed within 24 hours.</check>
      <check>Analysis completed: recurring themes identified, participant counts noted.</check>
      <check>Insights documented and shared with stakeholders.</check>
    </checklist>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.nngroup.com/articles/user-interviews/"/>
      <link href="https://rosenfeldmedia.com/books/interviewing-users/"/>
